711052f-a.text:
West 10th Street (formmerly Amos Street), north side, from Waverly Place (formerly Factory Street), to Greenwich Avenue, inclusive, seen from the roof of 45 Christopher Street, a tall new apartn.ent building east of Seventh avenue South. The neighborhood is lowgrade residential iu character. The car track on 10th Street is
the westbound track of the 8th Street crosstown line.
Greenwich Villagers of this period will recognise Julius's speakeasy, which will become a legal bar after Repeal, on the N.W. corner of Waverly Place. John and Gene's ("The Old Place"), on the north side between Greenwich Avenue and Waverly Place, is not visible in
this picture.
March 6, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.
